dom-dim-width.name: width
dom-dim-width.summary: The width property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a DOMString that reflects the width HTML attribute, specifying the displayed width of the resource in CSS pixels.
dom-dim-width.title: HTMLObjectElement.width

dom-cva-willvalidate.name: willValidate
dom-cva-willvalidate.summary: The willValidate read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a Boolean that indicates whether the element is a candidate for constraint validation. Always false for HTMLObjectElement objects.
dom-cva-willvalidate.title: HTMLObjectElement.willValidate

htmlobjectelement.name: HTMLObjectElement

htmloptgroupelement.name: HTMLOptGroupElement

The HTMLParagraphElement interface provides special properties (beyond those of the regular HTMLElement object interface it inherits) for manipulating

elements.

htmlpictureelement.name: HTMLPictureElement
htmlpictureelement.summary: The HTMLPictureElement interface represents a <picture> HTML element. It doesn't implement specific properties or methods.

htmlpreelement.summary: The HTMLPreElement interface exposes specific properties and methods (beyond those of the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating a block of preformatted text (<pre>).

htmlprogresselement.name: HTMLProgressElement

htmlquoteelement.name: HTMLQuoteElement
htmlquoteelement.summary: The HTMLQuoteElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating quoting elements, like <blockquote> and <q>, but not the <cite> element.

dom-script-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-script-referrerpolicy.summary: The referrerPolicy property of the HTMLScriptElement interface reflects the HTML referrerpolicy of the <script> element and fetches made by that script, defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.

dom-select-add.name: add
dom-select-add.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.add() method adds an element to the collection of option elements for this select element.

dom-fe-autofocus.name: autofocus
dom-fe-autofocus.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.autofocus property is a Boolean that reflects the autofocus HTML attribute, which indicates whether the associated <select> element  will get input focus when the page loads, unless the user overrides it.
dom-fe-autofocus.title: HTMLSelectElement.autofocus

dom-fe-disabled.name: disabled
dom-fe-disabled.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.disabled is a Boolean that reflects the disabled HTML attribute, which indicates whether the control is disabled. If it is disabled, it does not accept clicks. A disabled element is unusable and un-clickable.
dom-fe-disabled.title: HTMLSelectElement.disabled

dom-select-item.name: item
dom-select-item.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.item() method returns the Element corresponding to the HTMLOptionElement whose position in the options list corresponds to the index given in the parameter, or null if there are none.
dom-select-item.title: HTMLSelectElement.item()

dom-select-nameditem.name: namedItem
dom-select-nameditem.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.namedItem() method returns the HTMLOptionElement corresponding to the HTMLOptionElement whose name or id match the specified name, or null if no option matches.

ie.notes: namedItem does not appear to take the name attribute into account (only the id attribute) on Internet Explorer and Edge. There is a bug report to Microsoft about this.

dom-select-nameditem.title: HTMLSelectElement.namedItem()

dom-select-options.name: options
dom-select-options.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.options read-only property returns a HTMLOptionsCollection of the <option> elements contained by the <select> element.

dom-select-selectedindex.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.selectedIndex is a long that reflects the index of the first or last selected <option> element, depending on the value of multiple. The value -1 indicates that no element is selected.
dom-select-selectedindex.title: HTMLSelectElement.selectedIndex

dom-select-selectedoptions.name: selectedOptions
dom-select-selectedoptions.summary: The read-only HTMLSelectElement property selectedOptions contains a list of the <option> elements contained within the <select> element that are currently selected. dom-select-type.name: type
dom-select-type.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.type read-only property returns the form control's type.

htmlselectelement.name: HTMLSelectElement
htmlselectelement.summary: The HTMLSelectElement interface represents a <select> HTML Element. These elements also share all of the properties and methods of other HTML elements via the HTMLElement interface.

htmlselectelement.title: HTMLSelectElement

dom-slot-assignedelements.name: assignedElements
dom-slot-assignedelements.summary: The assignedElements() property of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns a sequence of the elements assigned to this slot (and no other nodes). dom-slot-assignednodes.name: assignedNodes
dom-slot-assignednodes.summary: The assignedNodes() property of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns a sequence of the nodes assigned to this slot, and if the flatten option is set to true, the assigned nodes of any other slots that are descendants of this slot. htmltablecolelement.name: HTMLTableColElement

dom-table-caption.name: caption

dom-table-createtfoot.summary: The HTMLTableElement.createTFoot() method returns the <tfoot> element associated with a given <table>. If no footer exists in the table, this methods creates it, and then returns it.

dom-table-createthead.name: createTHead
dom-table-createthead.summary: The HTMLTableElement.createTHead() method returns the <thead> element associated with a given <table>. If no header exists in the table, this method creates it, and then returns it.
dom-table-createthead.title: HTMLTableElement.createTHead()

dom-table-deletecaption.summary: The HTMLTableElement.deleteCaption() method removes the <caption> element from a given <table>. If there is no <caption> element associated with the table, this method does nothing.

dom-location-assign.name: assign

dom-location-hash.name: hash

dom-location-host.name: host
dom-location-host.summary: The host property of the Location interface is a USVString containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.
dom-location-host.title: Location: host

dom-location-hostname.name: hostname
dom-location-hostname.summary: The hostname property of the Location interface is a USVString containing the domain of the URL.

dom-location-href.name: href

dom-location-origin.name: origin

dom-location-port.name: port

dom-location-protocol.name: protocol
dom-location-protocol.summary: The protocol property of the Location interface is a USVString representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.

dom-location-reload.name: reload
dom-location-reload.summary: The Location.reload() method reloads the current URL, like the Refresh button.

dom-location-search.name: search
dom-location-search.summary: The search property of the Location interface is a search string, also called a query string; that is, a USVString containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

dom-navigator-online.name: onLine
dom-navigator-online.summary: Returns the online status of the browser. The property returns a boolean value, with true meaning online and false meaning offline. The property sends updates whenever the browser's ability to connect to the network changes. The update occurs when the user follows links or when a script requests a remote page. For example, the property should return false when users click links soon after they lose internet connection.

chrome.notes: Earlier versions of Chrome incorrectly return true when a tab is first opened, but it starts reporting the correct connectivity status after the first network event. Windows: 11, Mac: 14, Chrome OS: 13, Linux: Always returns true. For history, see crbug.com/7469.

firefox.notes: Since Firefox 4 the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity. Since Firefox 41, on OS X and Windows, the returned values follow the actual network connectivity, unless 'Work offline' mode is selected (where it will always return false).

ie.notes: in Internet Explorer 8 'online' and 'offline' events are raised on the document.body; under IE 9 they are raised on both document.body and window.

opera.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.

opera_android.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.

path2d-objects.name: Path2D
path2d-objects.summary: The Path2D interface of the Canvas 2D API is used to declare a path that can then be used on a CanvasRenderingContext2D object. The path methods of the CanvasRenderingContext2D interface are also present on this interface, which gives you the convenience of being able to retain and replay your path whenever desired.
path2d-objects.title: Path2D

dom-plugin.name: Plugin
dom-plugin.summary: The Plugin interface provides information about a browser plugin.
dom-plugin.title: Plugin

pluginarray.name: PluginArray
pluginarray.summary: The PluginArray interface is used to store a list of Plugin objects describing the available plugins; it's returned by the window.navigator.plugins property. The PluginArray is not a JavaScript array, but has the length property and supports accessing individual items using bracket notation (plugins[2]), as well as via item(index) and namedItem("name") methods.
pluginarray.title: PluginArray

popstateevent.name: PopStateEvent
popstateevent.summary: PopStateEvent is an event handler for the popstate event on the window.
popstateevent.title: PopStateEvent

the-promiserejectionevent-interface.name: PromiseRejectionEvent
the-promiserejectionevent-interface.summary: The PromiseRejectionEvent() constructor returns a newly created PromiseRejectionEvent, which represents events fired when a JavaScript Promise is rejected.
the-promiserejectionevent-interface.title: PromiseRejectionEvent()

dom-promiserejectionevent-promise.name: promise
dom-promiserejectionevent-promise.summary: The PromiseRejectionEvent interface's promise read-only property indicates the JavaScript Promise which was rejected. You can examine the event's PromiseRejectionEvent.reason property to learn why the promise was rejected.
dom-promiserejectionevent-promise.title: PromiseRejectionEvent.promise

dom-promiserejectionevent-reason.name: reason
dom-promiserejectionevent-reason.summary: The PromiseRejectionEvent reason read-only property is any JavaScript value or Object which provides the reason passed into Promise.reject(). This in theory provides information about why the promise was rejected.
dom-promiserejectionevent-reason.title: PromiseRejectionEvent.reason

promiserejectionevent.name: PromiseRejectionEvent
promiserejectionevent.summary: The PromiseRejectionEvent interface represents events which are sent to the global script context when JavaScript Promises are rejected.
promiserejectionevent.title: PromiseRejectionEvent

dom-radionodelist-value.name: value
dom-radionodelist-value.summary: If the underlying element collection contains radio buttons, the RadioNodeList.value property represents the checked radio button. On retrieving the value property, the value of the currently checked radio button is returned as a string. If the collection does not contain any radio buttons or none of the radio buttons in the collection is in checked state, the empty string is returned. On setting the value property, the first radio button input element whose value property is equal to the new value will be set to checked.
dom-radionodelist-value.title: RadioNodeList.value

radionodelist.name: RadioNodeList
radionodelist.summary: The RadioNodeList interface represents a collection of radio elements in a <form> or a <fieldset> element.
radionodelist.title: RadioNodeList

image-decoding-hint.name: decoding
image-decoding-hint.summary: The decoding property of the SVGImageElement interface represents a hint given to the browser on how it should decode the image.
image-decoding-hint.title: SVGImageElement.decoding

dom-sharedworker.name: SharedWorker
dom-sharedworker.summary: The SharedWorker() constructor creates a SharedWorker object that executes the script at the specified URL. This script must obey the same-origin policy.
dom-sharedworker.title: SharedWorker()

dom-sharedworker-port.name: port
dom-sharedworker-port.summary: The port property of the SharedWorker interface returns a MessagePort object used to communicate and control the shared worker.
dom-sharedworker-port.title: SharedWorker.port

sharedworker.name: SharedWorker
sharedworker.summary: The SharedWorker interface represents a specific kind of worker that can be accessed from several browsing contexts, such as several windows, iframes or even workers. They implement an interface different than dedicated workers and have a different global scope, SharedWorkerGlobalScope.
sharedworker.title: SharedWorker

dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-close.name: close
dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-close.summary: The close() method of the SharedWorkerGlobalScope interface discards any tasks queued in the SharedWorkerGlobalScope's event loop, effectively closing this particular scope.
dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-close.title: SharedWorkerGlobalScope.close()

event-workerglobalscope-connect.name: connect_event
event-workerglobalscope-connect.summary: The connect event is fired in shared workers at their SharedWorkerGlobalScope when a new client connects.

firefox.notes: Before version 65 the data property of the event object was null; it is now initialized to an empty string, as per spec.

firefox_android.notes: Before version 65 the data property of the event object was null; it is now initialized to an empty string, as per spec.

event-workerglobalscope-connect.title: SharedWorkerGlobalScope: connect event

dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-name.name: name
dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-name.summary: The name read-only property of the SharedWorkerGlobalScope interface returns the name that the SharedWorker was (optionally) given when it was created. This is the name that the SharedWorker() constructor can pass to get a reference to the SharedWorkerGlobalScope.
dom-sharedworkerglobalscope-name.title: SharedWorkerGlobalScope.name

handler-sharedworkerglobalscope-onconnec.name: onconnect
handler-sharedworkerglobalscope-onconnec.summary: The onconnect property of the SharedWorkerGlobalScope interface is an event handler representing the code to be called when the connect event is raised  that is, when a MessagePort connection is opened between the associated SharedWorker and the main thread.
handler-sharedworkerglobalscope-onconnec.title: SharedWorkerGlobalScope.onconnect

sharedworkerglobalscope.name: SharedWorkerGlobalScope
sharedworkerglobalscope.summary: The SharedWorkerGlobalScope object (the SharedWorker global scope) is accessible through the self keyword. Some additional global functions, namespaces objects, and constructors, not typically associated with the worker global scope, but available on it, are listed in the JavaScript Reference. See the complete list of functions available to workers.
sharedworkerglobalscope.title: SharedWorkerGlobalScope

dom-storage-clear.name: clear
dom-storage-clear.summary: The clear() method of the Storage interface clears all keys stored in a given Storage object.
dom-storage-clear.title: Storage.clear()

dom-storage-getitem.name: getItem
dom-storage-getitem.summary: The getItem() method of the Storage interface, when passed a key name, will return that key's value, or null if the key does not exist, in the given Storage object.
dom-storage-getitem.title: Storage.getItem()

dom-storage-key.name: key
dom-storage-key.summary: The key() method of the Storage interface, when passed a number n, returns the name of the nth key in a given Storage object. The order of keys is user-agent defined, so you should not rely on it.
dom-storage-key.title: Storage.key()

dom-storage-length.name: length
dom-storage-length.summary: The length read-only property of the Storage interface returns the number of data items stored in a given Storage object.
dom-storage-length.title: Storage.length

dom-storage-removeitem.name: removeItem
dom-storage-removeitem.summary: The removeItem() method of the Storage interface, when passed a key name, will remove that key from the given Storage object if it exists. The Storage interface of the Web Storage API provides access to a particular domain's session or local storage.
dom-storage-removeitem.title: Storage.removeItem()

dom-storage-setitem.name: setItem
dom-storage-setitem.summary: The setItem() method of the Storage interface, when passed a key name and value, will add that key to the given Storage object, or update that key's value if it already exists.
dom-storage-setitem.title: Storage.setItem()

storage.name: Storage
storage.summary: The Storage interface of the Web Storage API provides access to a particular domain's session or local storage. It allows, for example, the addition, modification, or deletion of stored data items.
storage.title: Storage

the-storageevent-interface.name: StorageEvent
the-storageevent-interface.summary: A StorageEvent is sent to a window when a storage area it has access to is changed within the context of another document.
the-storageevent-interface.title: StorageEvent

submitevent.name: SubmitEvent
submitevent.summary: The SubmitEvent() constructor creates and returns a new SubmitEvent object, which is used to represent a submit event fired at an HTML form.
submitevent.title: SubmitEvent()

dom-submitevent-submitter.name: submitter
dom-submitevent-submitter.summary: The read-only submitter property found on the SubmitEvent interface specifies the submit button or other element that was invoked to cause the form to be submitted.
dom-submitevent-submitter.title: SubmitEvent.submitter

the-submitevent-interface.name: SubmitEvent
the-submitevent-interface.summary: The SubmitEvent interface defines the object used to represent an HTML form's submit event. This event is fired at the <form> when the form's submit action is invoked.
the-submitevent-interface.title: SubmitEvent

dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxascent.name: actualBoundingBoxAscent
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxascent.summary: The read-only actualBoundingBoxAscent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline attribute to the top of the bounding rectangle used to render the text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxascent.title: TextMetrics.actualBoundingBoxAscent

dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxdescent.name: actualBoundingBoxDescent
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxdescent.summary: The read-only actualBoundingBoxDescent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline attribute to the bottom of the bounding rectangle used to render the text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxdescent.title: TextMetrics.actualBoundingBoxDescent

dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxleft.name: actualBoundingBoxLeft
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxleft.summary: The read-only actualBoundingBoxLeft property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance parallel to the baseline from the alignment point given by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textAlign property to the left side of the bounding rectangle of the given text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxleft.title: TextMetrics.actualBoundingBoxLeft

dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxright.name: actualBoundingBoxRight
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxright.summary: The read-only actualBoundingBoxRight property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance parallel to the baseline from the alignment point given by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textAlign property to the right side of the bounding rectangle of the given text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-actualboundingboxright.title: TextMetrics.actualBoundingBoxRight

dom-textmetrics-alphabeticbaseline.name: alphabeticBaseline
dom-textmetrics-alphabeticbaseline.summary: The read-only alphabeticBaseline property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline property to the alphabetic baseline of the line box, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-alphabeticbaseline.title: TextMetrics.alphabeticBaseline

dom-textmetrics-emheightascent.name: emHeightAscent
dom-textmetrics-emheightascent.summary: The read-only emHeightAscent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline property to the top of the em square in the line box, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-emheightascent.title: TextMetrics.emHeightAscent

dom-textmetrics-emheightdescent.name: emHeightDescent
dom-textmetrics-emheightdescent.summary: The read-only emHeightDescent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline property to the bottom of the em square in the line box, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-emheightdescent.title: TextMetrics.emHeightDescent

dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxascent.name: fontBoundingBoxAscent
dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxascent.summary: The read-only fontBoundingBoxAscent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline attribute to the top of the highest bounding rectangle of all the fonts used to render the text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxascent.title: TextMetrics.fontBoundingBoxAscent

dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxdescent.name: fontBoundingBoxDescent
dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxdescent.summary: The read-only fontBoundingBoxDescent property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline attribute to the bottom of the bounding rectangle of all the fonts used to render the text, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-fontboundingboxdescent.title: TextMetrics.fontBoundingBoxDescent

dom-textmetrics-hangingbaseline.name: hangingBaseline
dom-textmetrics-hangingbaseline.summary: The read-only hangingBaseline property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline property to the hanging baseline of the line box, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-hangingbaseline.title: TextMetrics.hangingBaseline

dom-textmetrics-ideographicbaseline.name: ideographicBaseline
dom-textmetrics-ideographicbaseline.summary: The read-only ideographicBaseline property of the TextMetrics interface is a double giving the distance from the horizontal line indicated by the CanvasRenderingContext2D.textBaseline property to the ideographic baseline of the line box, in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-ideographicbaseline.title: TextMetrics.ideographicBaseline

dom-textmetrics-width.name: width
dom-textmetrics-width.summary: The read-only width property of the TextMetrics interface contains the text's advance width (the width of that inline box) in CSS pixels.
dom-textmetrics-width.title: TextMetrics.width

textmetrics.name: TextMetrics
textmetrics.summary: The TextMetrics interface represents the dimensions of a piece of text in the canvas; a textMetrics() instance can be retrieved using the CanvasRenderingContext2D.measureText() method.
textmetrics.title: TextMetrics

dom-texttrack-mode.name: mode
dom-texttrack-mode.summary: The TextTrack interface's mode property is a string specifying and controlling the text track's mode: disabled, hidden, or showing.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 52, using JavaScript to change the mode of a text track that's part of a media element would send one change event to the element's textTracks TextTrackList for each change, even if mutliple changes are made in a single pass through the Firefox event loop. Starting in Firefox 52, these changes are reflected by a single event.

dom-texttrack-mode.title: TextTrack.mode

texttrack.name: TextTrack
texttrack.summary: This interface also inherits properties from EventTarget.

firefox.notes: Firefox versions before Firefox 50 didn't display captions when playing media without one or more video tracks being played.

texttrack.title: TextTrack

texttrackcue.name: TextTrackCue
texttrackcue.summary: TextTrackCue is an abstract class which is used as the basis for the various derived cue types, such as VTTCue; you will instead work with those derived types.
texttrackcue.title: TextTrackCue

dom-texttracklist-gettrackbyid.name: getTrackById
dom-texttracklist-gettrackbyid.summary: The TextTrackList method getTrackById() returns the first TextTrack object from the track list whose id matches the specified string.
dom-texttracklist-gettrackbyid.title: getTrackById()

dom-texttracklist-length.name: length
dom-texttracklist-length.summary: The read-only TextTrackList property length returns the number of entries in the TextTrackList, each of which is a TextTrack representing one track in the media element.
dom-texttracklist-length.title: TextTrackList.length

texttracklist.name: TextTrackList
texttracklist.summary: The TextTrackList interface is used to represent a list of the text tracks defined by the <track> element, with each track represented by a separate textTrack object in the list.
texttracklist.title: TextTrackList

dom-timeranges-end.name: end
dom-timeranges-end.summary: Returns the time offset at which a specified time range ends.
dom-timeranges-end.title: TimeRanges.end()

dom-timeranges-length.name: length
dom-timeranges-length.summary: The TimeRanges.length read-only property returns the number of ranges in the object.
dom-timeranges-length.title: TimeRanges.length

dom-timeranges-start.name: start
dom-timeranges-start.summary: Returns the time offset at which a specified time range begins.
dom-timeranges-start.title: TimeRanges.start()

time-ranges.name: TimeRanges
time-ranges.summary: The TimeRanges interface is used to represent a set of time ranges, primarily for the purpose of tracking which portions of media have been buffered when loading it for use by the <audio> and <video> elements.
time-ranges.title: TimeRanges

dom-trackevent-track.name: track
dom-trackevent-track.summary: The read-only track property of the TrackEvent interface specifies the media track object to which the event applies.
dom-trackevent-track.title: TrackEvent.track

the-trackevent-interface.name: TrackEvent
the-trackevent-interface.summary: The TrackEvent interface, which is part of the HTML DOM specification, is used for events which represent changes to a set of available tracks on an HTML media element; these events are addtrack and removetrack.
the-trackevent-interface.title: TrackEvent

transferable-objects.name: Transferable
transferable-objects.summary: The Transferable interface represents an object that can be transfered between different execution contexts, like the main thread and Web workers.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer 10 only accepts a single Transferable object as parameter, but not an array.

transferable-objects.title: Transferable

dom-validitystate-badinput.name: badInput
dom-validitystate-badinput.summary: The read-only badInput property of a ValidityState object indicates if the user has provided input that the browser is unable to convert. For example, if you have a number input element whose content is a string. Note: While this is unsupported in Internet Explorer, any non-numeric value will be dismissed from the field if it is a number input.
dom-validitystate-badinput.title: validityState.badInput

dom-validitystate-toolong.name: tooLong
dom-validitystate-toolong.summary: The read-only tooLong property of a ValidityState object indicates if the value of an <input> or <textarea>, after having been edited by the user, exceeds the maximum code-unit length established by the element's maxlength attribute.

firefox.notes: Not supported in the unlikely case of the value being initially set too long, and then changed by the user to a still incorrect state. Per caniuse.com.

dom-validitystate-toolong.title: validityState.tooLong

dom-validitystate-tooshort.name: tooShort
dom-validitystate-tooshort.summary: The read-only tooShort property of a ValidityState object indicates if the value of an <input>, <button>, <select>, <output>, <fieldset> or <textarea>, after having been edited by the user, is less than the minimum code-unit length established by the element's minlength attribute.
dom-validitystate-tooshort.title: validityState.tooShort

validitystate.name: ValidityState
validitystate.summary: The ValidityState interface represents the validity states that an element can be in, with respect to constraint validation. Together, they help explain why an element's value fails to validate, if it's not valid.
validitystate.title: ValidityState

dom-videotrack-id.name: id
dom-videotrack-id.summary: The id property contains a string which uniquely identifies the track represented by the VideoTrack.
dom-videotrack-id.title: VideoTrack.id

dom-videotrack-kind.name: kind
dom-videotrack-kind.summary: The kind property contains a string indicating the category of video contained in the VideoTrack.
dom-videotrack-kind.title: VideoTrack.kind

dom-videotrack-label.name: label
dom-videotrack-label.summary: The read-only VideoTrack property label returns a string specifying the video track's human-readable label, if one is available; otherwise, it returns an empty string.
dom-videotrack-label.title: VideoTrack.label

dom-videotrack-language.name: language
dom-videotrack-language.summary: The read-only VideoTrack property language returns a string identifying the language used in the video track.
dom-videotrack-language.title: Videotrack.language

dom-videotrack-selected.name: selected
dom-videotrack-selected.summary: The VideoTrack property selected controls whether or not a particular video track is active.
dom-videotrack-selected.title: VideoTrack.selected

videotrack.name: VideoTrack
videotrack.summary: The VideoTrack interface represents a single video track from a <video> element.
videotrack.title: VideoTrack

dom-videotracklist-gettrackbyid.name: getTrackById
dom-videotracklist-gettrackbyid.summary: The VideoTrackList method getTrackById() returns the first VideoTrack object from the track list whose id matches the specified string.
dom-videotracklist-gettrackbyid.title: getTrackById

dom-videotracklist-length.name: length
dom-videotracklist-length.summary: The read-only VideoTrackList property length returns the number of entries in the VideoTrackList, each of which is a VideoTrack representing one video track in the media element.
dom-videotracklist-length.title: VideoTrackList.length

dom-videotracklist-selectedindex.name: selectedIndex
dom-videotracklist-selectedindex.summary: The read-only VideoTrackList property selectedIndex returns the index of the currently selected track, if any, or -1 otherwise.
dom-videotracklist-selectedindex.title: VideoTrackList.selectedIndex

videotracklist.name: VideoTrackList
videotracklist.summary: The VideoTrackList interface is used to represent a list of the video tracks contained within a <video> element, with each track represented by a separate VideoTrack object in the list.
videotracklist.title: VideoTrackList

offscreencontext-commit.name: commit
offscreencontext-commit.summary: The WebGLRenderingContext.commit() method pushes frames back to the original HTMLCanvasElement, if the context is not directly fixed to a specific canvas.
offscreencontext-commit.title: WebGLRenderingContext.commit()

dom-websocket.name: WebSocket
dom-websocket.summary: The WebSocket() constructor returns a new WebSocket object.

firefox.notes: Parameter protocols not supported.

dom-websocket.title: WebSocket()

dom-websocket-binarytype.name: binaryType
dom-websocket-binarytype.summary: The WebSocket.binaryType property returns the type of binary data being transmitted by the connection.
dom-websocket-binarytype.title: WebSocket.binaryType

dom-websocket-bufferedamount.name: bufferedAmount
dom-websocket-bufferedamount.summary: The WebSocket.bufferedAmount read-only property returns the number of bytes of data that have been queued using calls to send() but not yet transmitted to the network. This value resets to zero once all queued data has been sent. This value does not reset to zero when the connection is closed; if you keep calling send(), this will continue to climb.
dom-websocket-bufferedamount.title: WebSocket.bufferedAmount

dom-websocket-close.name: close
dom-websocket-close.summary: The WebSocket.close() method closes the WebSocket connection or connection attempt, if any. If the connection is already CLOSED, this method does nothing.

firefox.notes: Parameters not supported, see bug 674716.

firefox_android.notes: Parameters not supported, see bug 674716.

dom-websocket-close.title: WebSocket.close()

dom-websocket-extensions.name: extensions
dom-websocket-extensions.summary: The WebSocket.extensions read-only property returns the extensions selected by the server. This is currently only the empty string or a list of extensions as negotiated by the connection.
dom-websocket-extensions.title: WebSocket.extensions

handler-websocket-onclose.name: onclose
handler-websocket-onclose.summary: The WebSocket.onclose property is an EventHandler that is called when the WebSocket connection's readyState changes to CLOSED. It is called with a CloseEvent.
handler-websocket-onclose.title: WebSocket.onclose

handler-websocket-onerror.name: onerror
handler-websocket-onerror.summary: The WebSocket interface's onerror event handler property is a function which gets called when an error occurs on the WebSocket.
handler-websocket-onerror.title: WebSocket.onerror

handler-websocket-onmessage.name: onmessage
handler-websocket-onmessage.summary: The WebSocket.onmessage property is an EventHandler that is called when a message is received from the server. It is called with a MessageEvent.
handler-websocket-onmessage.title: WebSocket.onmessage

handler-websocket-onopen.name: onopen
handler-websocket-onopen.summary: The WebSocket.onopen property is an EventHandler that is called when the WebSocket connection's readyState changes to 1; this indicates that the connection is ready to send and receive data. It is called with an Event.
handler-websocket-onopen.title: WebSocket.onopen

dom-websocket-protocol.name: protocol
dom-websocket-protocol.summary: The WebSocket.protocol read-only property returns the name of the sub-protocol the server selected; this will be one of the strings specified in the protocols parameter when creating the WebSocket object, or the empty string if no connection is established.
dom-websocket-protocol.title: WebSocket.protocol

dom-websocket-readystate.name: readyState
dom-websocket-readystate.summary: The WebSocket.readyState read-only property returns the current state of the WebSocket connection.
dom-websocket-readystate.title: WebSocket.readyState

dom-websocket-send.name: send
dom-websocket-send.summary: The WebSocket.send() method enqueues the specified data to be transmitted to the server over the WebSocket connection, increasing the value of bufferedAmount by the number of bytes needed to contain the data. If the data can't be sent (for example, because it needs to be buffered but the buffer is full), the socket is closed automatically.

firefox.notes: See bug 775368.
Only parameter of type ArrayBuffer and String supported.

Only parameter of type String supported. Returns boolean.

firefox_android.notes: See bug 775368.

Only parameter of type String supported.
Only parameter of type String supported. Returns boolean.

dom-websocket-send.title: WebSocket.send()

dom-websocket-url.name: url
dom-websocket-url.summary: The WebSocket.url read-only property returns the absolute URL of the WebSocket as resolved by the constructor.
dom-websocket-url.title: WebSocket.url

network.name: WebSocket
network.summary: The WebSocket object provides the API for creating and managing a WebSocket connection to a server, as well as for sending and receiving data on the connection.

event-domcontentloaded.name: DOMContentLoaded_event
event-domcontentloaded.summary: The DOMContentLoaded event fires when the initial HTML document has been completely loaded and parsed, without waiting for stylesheets, images, and subframes to finish loading.
event-domcontentloaded.title: Window: DOMContentLoaded event

event-afterprint.name: afterprint_event
event-afterprint.summary: The afterprint event is fired after the associated document has started printing or the print preview has been closed.
event-afterprint.title: Window: afterprint event

dom-alert.name: alert
dom-alert.summary: The Window.alert() method displays an alert dialog with the optional specified content and an OK button.

chrome.notes: Starting with Chrome 46, this method is blocked inside an <iframe> unless its sandbox attribute has the value allow-modals.

dom-alert.title: Window.alert()

event-beforeprint.name: beforeprint_event
event-beforeprint.summary: The beforeprint event is fired when the associated document is about to be printed or previewed for printing.
event-beforeprint.title: Window: beforeprint event

event-beforeunload.name: beforeunload_event
event-beforeunload.summary: The beforeunload event is fired when the window, the document and its resources are about to be unloaded.
event-beforeunload.title: Window: beforeunload event

dom-window-blur.name: blur
dom-window-blur.summary: Shifts focus away from the window.
dom-window-blur.title: Window.blur()

animationframeprovider-cancelanimationfr.name: cancelAnimationFrame
animationframeprovider-cancelanimationfr.summary: The window.cancelAnimationFrame() method cancels an animation frame request previously scheduled through a call to window.requestAnimationFrame().
animationframeprovider-cancelanimationfr.title: window.cancelAnimationFrame()

dom-window-close.name: close
dom-window-close.summary: The Window.close() method closes the current window, or the window on which it was called.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 46.0.1, Window.close() can no longer close windows that weren't opened by the same script. This is a security precaution.

firefox_android.notes: Starting in Firefox 46.0.1, Window.close() can no longer close windows that weren't opened by the same script. This is a security precaution.

dom-window-close.title: Window.close()

dom-confirm.name: confirm

dom-workerglobalscope-importscripts.name: importScripts
dom-workerglobalscope-importscripts.summary: The importScripts() method of the WorkerGlobalScope interface synchronously imports one or more scripts into the worker's scope.
dom-workerglobalscope-importscripts.title: WorkerGlobalScope.importScripts()

dom-workerglobalscope-location.name: location
dom-workerglobalscope-location.summary: The location read-only property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface returns the WorkerLocation associated with the worker. It is a specific location object, mostly a subset of the Location for browsing scopes, but adapted to workers.
dom-workerglobalscope-location.title: WorkerGlobalScope.location

dom-worker-navigator.name: navigator
dom-worker-navigator.summary: The navigator read-only property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface returns the WorkerNavigator associated with the worker. It is a specific navigator object, mostly a subset of the Navigator for browsing scopes, but adapted to workers.
dom-worker-navigator.title: WorkerGlobalScope.navigator

handler-workerglobalscope-onerror.name: onerror
handler-workerglobalscope-onerror.summary: The onerror property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface represents an EventHandler to be called when the error event occurs and bubbles through the Worker.
handler-workerglobalscope-onerror.title: WorkerGlobalScope.onerror

handler-workerglobalscope-onlanguagechan.name: onlanguagechange
handler-workerglobalscope-onlanguagechan.summary: The onlanguagechange property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface represents an EventHandler to be called when the languagechange event occurs and bubbles through the Worker.
handler-workerglobalscope-onlanguagechan.title: WorkerGlobalScope.onlanguagechange

handler-workerglobalscope-onoffline.name: onoffline
handler-workerglobalscope-onoffline.summary: The onoffline property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface represents an EventHandler to be called when the offline event occurs and bubbles through the Worker.
handler-workerglobalscope-onoffline.title: WorkerGlobalScope.onoffline

handler-workerglobalscope-ononline.name: ononline
handler-workerglobalscope-ononline.summary: The ononline property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface represents an EventHandler to be called when the online event occurs and bubbles through the Worker.
handler-workerglobalscope-ononline.title: WorkerGlobalScope.ononline

dom-workerglobalscope-self.name: self
dom-workerglobalscope-self.summary: The self read-only property of the WorkerGlobalScope interface returns a reference to the WorkerGlobalScope itself. Most of the time it is a specific scope like DedicatedWorkerGlobalScope,  SharedWorkerGlobalScope, or ServiceWorkerGlobalScope.
dom-workerglobalscope-self.title: WorkerGlobalScope.self

workerglobalscope.name: WorkerGlobalScope
workerglobalscope.summary: The WorkerGlobalScope interface of the Web Workers API is an interface representing the scope of any worker. Workers have no browsing context; this scope contains the information usually conveyed by Window objects  in this case event handlers, the console or the associated WorkerNavigator object. Each WorkerGlobalScope has its own event loop.
workerglobalscope.title: WorkerGlobalScope

workerlocation.name: WorkerLocation
workerlocation.summary: The WorkerLocation interface defines the absolute location of the script executed by the Worker. Such an object is initialized for each worker and is available via the WorkerGlobalScope.location property obtained by calling self.location.
workerlocation.title: WorkerLocation

workernavigator.name: WorkerNavigator
workernavigator.summary: The WorkerNavigator interface represents a subset of the Navigator interface allowed to be accessed from a Worker. Such an object is initialized for each worker and is available via the WorkerGlobalScope.navigator property obtained by calling window.self.navigator.
workernavigator.title: WorkerNavigator

selector-active.name: active
selector-active.summary: The :active CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as a button) that is being activated by the user.
selector-active.title: :active

selector-checked.name: checked
selector-checked.summary: The :checked CSS pseudo-class selector represents any radio (<input type="radio">), checkbox (<input type="checkbox">), or option (<option> in a <select>) element that is checked or toggled to an on state.

chrome.notes: On macOS, styling <option&rt; elements has no effect.

selector-default.name: default
selector-default.summary: The :default CSS pseudo-class selects form elements that are the default in a group of related elements.
selector-default.title: :default

selector-defined.name: defined
selector-defined.summary: The :defined CSS pseudo-class represents any element that has been defined. This includes any standard element built in to the browser, and custom elements that have been successfully defined (i.e. with the CustomElementRegistry.define() method).
selector-defined.title: :defined

selector-ltr.name: dir
selector-ltr.summary: The :dir() CSS pseudo-class matches elements based on the directionality of the text contained in them.
selector-ltr.title: :dir()

selector-disabled.name: disabled
selector-disabled.summary: The :disabled CSS pseudo-class represents any disabled element. An element is disabled if it can't be activated (selected, clicked on, typed into, etc.) or accept focus. The element also has an enabled state, in which it can be activated or accept focus.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer does not recognize :disabled on the <fieldset> element.

selector-disabled.title: :disabled

selector-enabled.name: enabled
selector-enabled.summary: The :enabled CSS pseudo-class represents any enabled element. An element is enabled if it can be activated (selected, clicked on, typed into, etc.) or accept focus. The element also has a disabled state, in which it can't be activated or accept focus.
selector-enabled.title: :enabled

selector-focus.name: focus
selector-focus.summary: The :focus CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as a form input) that has received focus. It is generally triggered when the user clicks or taps on an element or selects it with the keyboard's Tab key.
selector-focus.title: :focus

selector-hover.name: hover
selector-hover.summary: The :hover CSS pseudo-class matches when the user interacts with an element with a pointing device, but does not necessarily activate it. It is generally triggered when the user hovers over an element with the cursor (mouse pointer).

safari_ios.notes: As of Safari for iOS 7.1.2, tapping a clickable element causes the element to enter the :hover state. The element will remain in the :hover state until a different element has entered the :hover state.

selector-hover.title: :hover

selector-in-range.name: in-range
selector-in-range.summary: The :in-range CSS pseudo-class represents an <input> element whose current value is within the range limits specified by the min and max attributes.

selector-indeterminate.name: indeterminate
selector-indeterminate.summary: The :indeterminate CSS pseudo-class represents any form element whose state is indeterminate, such as checkboxes which have their HTML indeterminate attribute set to true, radio buttons which are members of a group in which all radio buttons are unchecked, and indeterminate <progress> elements.
selector-indeterminate.title: :indeterminate

selector-invalid.name: invalid
selector-invalid.summary: The :invalid CSS pseudo-class represents any <input> or other <form> element whose contents fail to validate.
selector-invalid.title: :invalid

selector-link.name: link
selector-link.summary: The :link CSS pseudo-class represents an element that has not yet been visited. It matches every unvisited <a>, <area>, or <link> element that has an href attribute.
selector-link.title: :link

selector-optional.name: optional
selector-optional.summary: The :optional CSS pseudo-class represents any <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element that does not have the required attribute set on it.
selector-optional.title: :optional

selector-out-of-range.name: out-of-range
selector-out-of-range.summary: The :out-of-range CSS pseudo-class represents an <input> element whose current value is outside the range limits specified by the min and max attributes.
selector-out-of-range.title: :out-of-range

selector-read-only.name: read-only
selector-read-only.summary: The :read-only CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as input or textarea) that is not editable by the user.
selector-read-only.title: :read-only

selector-read-write.name: read-write
selector-read-write.summary: The :read-write CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as input or textarea) that is editable by the user.
selector-read-write.title: :read-write

selector-required.name: required
selector-required.summary: The :required CSS pseudo-class represents any <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element that has the required attribute set on it.
selector-required.title: :required

selector-target.name: target
selector-target.summary: The :target CSS pseudo-class represents a unique element (the target element) with an id matching the URL's fragment.
selector-target.title: :target

selector-valid.name: valid
selector-valid.summary: The :valid CSS pseudo-class represents any <input> or other <form> element whose contents validate successfully. This allows to easily make valid fields adopt an appearance that helps the user confirm that their data is formatted properly.
selector-valid.title: :valid

selector-visited.name: visited
selector-visited.summary: The :visited CSS pseudo-class represents links that the user has already visited. For privacy reasons, the styles that can be modified using this selector are very limited.
selector-visited.title: :visited

link-type-noopener.name: noopener
link-type-noopener.summary: The noopener keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser to navigate to the target resource without granting the new browsing context access to the document that opened it  by not setting the Window.opener property on the opened window (it returns null).

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 63, rel="noopener" created windows with all features disabled by default. Starting with Firefox 63, these windows have the same features enabled by default as any other window.

link-type-noreferrer.name: noreferrer
link-type-noreferrer.summary: The noreferrer keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser, when navigating to the target resource, to omit the Referer header and otherwise leak no referrer information  and additionally to behave as if the noopener keyword were also specified.

the-a-element.name: a
the-a-element.summary: The HTML <a> element (or anchor element), with its href attribute, creates a hyperlink to web pages, files, email addresses, locations in the same page, or anything else a URL can address.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 41, <a> without href attribute is no longer classified as interactive content: clicking it inside <label> will activate labelled content (bug 1167816).

firefox_android.notes: Starting with Firefox 41, <a> without href attribute is no longer classified as interactive content: clicking it inside <label> will activate labelled content (bug 1167816).

the-a-element.title: <a>: The Anchor element

the-abbr-element.name: abbr
the-abbr-element.summary: The HTML Abbreviation element (<abbr>) represents an abbreviation or acronym; the optional title attribute can provide an expansion or description for the abbreviation.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-abbr-element.title: <abbr>: The Abbreviation element

the-address-element.name: address
the-address-element.summary: The HTML <address> element indicates that the enclosed HTML provides contact information for a person or people, or for an organization.
the-address-element.title: <address>: The Contact Address element

the-area-element.name: area
the-area-element.summary: The HTML <area> tag defines an area inside an image map that has predefined clickable areas. An image map allows geometric areas on an image to be associated with hypertext link.
the-area-element.title: <area>

the-article-element.name: article
the-article-element.summary: The HTML <article> element represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication).
the-article-element.title: <article>: The Article Contents element

the-aside-element.name: aside
the-aside-element.summary: The HTML <aside> element represents a portion of a document whose content is only indirectly related to the document's main content.
the-aside-element.title: <aside>: The Aside element

the-audio-element.name: audio
the-audio-element.summary: The HTML <audio> element is used to embed sound content in documents. It may contain one or more audio sources, represented using the src attribute or the <source> element: the browser will choose the most suitable one. It can also be the destination for streamed media, using a MediaStream.

firefox.notes: For Firefox to play audio, the server must serve the file using the correct MIME type.

firefox_android.notes: For Firefox to play audio, the server must serve the file using the correct MIME type.

the-audio-element.title: <audio>: The Embed Audio element

the-b-element.name: b
the-b-element.summary: The HTML Bring Attention To element (<b>) is used to draw the reader's attention to the element's contents, which are not otherwise granted special importance.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-b-element.title: <b>: The Bring Attention To element

the-base-element.name: base
the-base-element.summary: The HTML <base> element specifies the base URL to use for all relative URLs in a document.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 7, <base> can be positioned anywhere in the document and the nearest value of <base> is used.

the-base-element.title: <base>: The Document Base URL element

the-bdi-element.name: bdi
the-bdi-element.summary: The HTML Bidirectional Isolate element (<bdi>)  tells the browser's bidirectional algorithm to treat the text it contains in isolation from its surrounding text.
the-bdi-element.title: <bdi>: The Bidirectional Isolate element

the-bdo-element.name: bdo
the-bdo-element.summary: The HTML Bidirectional Text Override element (<bdo>) overrides the current directionality of text, so that the text within is rendered in a different direction.
the-bdo-element.title: <bdo>: The Bidirectional Text Override element

the-blockquote-element.name: blockquote
the-blockquote-element.summary: The HTML <blockquote> Element (or HTML Block Quotation Element) indicates that the enclosed text is an extended quotation. Usually, this is rendered visually by indentation (see Notes for how to change it). A URL for the source of the quotation may be given using the cite attribute, while a text representation of the source can be given using the <cite> element.
the-blockquote-element.title: <blockquote>: The Block Quotation element

the-body-element.name: body
the-body-element.summary: The HTML <body> Element represents the content of an HTML document. There can be only one <body> element in a document.
the-body-element.title: <body>: The Document Body element

the-br-element.name: br
the-br-element.summary:
The HTML
element produces a line break in text (carriage-return). It is useful for writing a poem or an address, where the division of lines is significant.
the-br-element.title: : The Line Break element

the-button-element.name: button
the-button-element.summary: The HTML <button> element represents a clickable button, used to submit forms or anywhere in a document for accessible, standard button functionality.
the-button-element.title: <button>: The Button element

the-canvas-element.name: canvas
the-canvas-element.summary: Use the HTML <canvas> element with either the canvas scripting API or the WebGL API to draw graphics and animations.

notes: Before Firefox 5, the canvas width and height were signed integers instead of unsigned integers.
Prior to Firefox 6, a <canvas> element with a zero width or height would be rendered as if it had default dimensions.

Before Firefox 12, if JavaScript is disabled, the <canvas> element was being rendered instead of showing the fallback content as per the specification. Since then, the fallback content is rendered instead.

the-canvas-element.title: <canvas>: The Graphics Canvas element

the-caption-element.name: caption
the-caption-element.summary: The HTML <caption> element specifies the caption (or title) of a table.
the-caption-element.title: <caption>: The Table Caption element

the-cite-element.name: cite
the-cite-element.summary: The HTML Citation element (<cite>) is used to describe a reference to a cited creative work, and must include the title of that work.
the-cite-element.title: <cite>: The Citation element

the-code-element.name: code
the-code-element.summary: The HTML <code> element displays its contents styled in a fashion intended to indicate that the text is a short fragment of computer code.
the-code-element.title: <code>: The Inline Code element

the-col-element.name: col
the-col-element.summary: The HTML <col> element defines a column within a table and is used for defining common semantics on all common cells. It is generally found within a <colgroup> element.
the-col-element.title: <col>

the-colgroup-element.name: colgroup
the-colgroup-element.summary: The HTML <colgroup> element defines a group of columns within a table.
the-colgroup-element.title: <colgroup>

the-data-element.name: data
the-data-element.summary: The HTML <data> element links a given piece of content with a machine-readable translation. If the content is time- or date-related, the <time> element must be used.
the-data-element.title: <data>

the-datalist-element.name: datalist
the-datalist-element.summary: The HTML <datalist> element contains a set of <option> elements that represent the permissible or recommended options available to choose from within other controls.

firefox_android.notes: Since Firefox for Android 79, the dropdown menu containing available options does not appear. See bug 1535985.

opera_android.notes: The dropdown menu containing available options does not appear in Opera for Android.

the-datalist-element.title: <datalist>: The HTML Data List element

the-dd-element.name: dd
the-dd-element.summary: The HTML <dd> element provides the description, definition, or value for the preceding term (<dt>) in a description list (<dl>).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element was implemented using the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of HTMLElement.

the-dd-element.title: <dd>: The Description Details element

the-del-element.name: del
the-del-element.summary: The HTML <del> element represents a range of text that has been deleted from a document.
the-del-element.title: <del>: The Deleted Text element

the-details-element.name: details
the-details-element.summary: The HTML Details Element (<details>) creates a disclosure widget in which information is visible only when the widget is toggled into an "open" state.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 57, there was a bug meaning that <details> elements can't be made open by default using the open attribute if they have a CSS animation active on them.

firefox_android.notes: There is a bug meaning that <details> elements can't be made open by default using the open attribute if they have a CSS animation active on them.

the-details-element.title: <details>: The Details disclosure element

the-dfn-element.name: dfn
the-dfn-element.summary: The HTML Definition element (<dfn>) is used to indicate the term being defined within the context of a definition phrase or sentence.
the-dfn-element.title: <dfn>: The Definition element

the-dialog-element.name: dialog
the-dialog-element.summary: The HTML <dialog> element represents a dialog box or other interactive component, such as a dismissable alert, inspector, or subwindow.

firefox.notes: See bug 840640.

firefox_android.notes: See bug 840640.

the-dialog-element.title: <dialog>: The Dialog element

the-div-element.name: div
the-div-element.summary: The HTML Content Division element (<div>) is the generic container for flow content. It has no effect on the content or layout until styled using CSS.
the-div-element.title: <div>: The Content Division element

the-dl-element.name: dl
the-dl-element.summary: The HTML <dl> element represents a description list. The element encloses a list of groups of terms (specified using the <dt> element) and descriptions (provided by <dd> elements). Common uses for this element are to implement a glossary or to display metadata (a list of key-value pairs).
the-dl-element.title: <dl>: The Description List element

the-dt-element.name: dt
the-dt-element.summary: The HTML <dt> element specifies a term in a description or definition list, and as such must be used inside a <dl> element.
the-dt-element.title: <dt>: The Description Term element

the-em-element.name: em
the-em-element.summary: The HTML <em> element marks text that has stress emphasis. The <em> element can be nested, with each level of nesting indicating a greater degree of emphasis.
the-em-element.title: <em>: The Emphasis element

the-embed-element.name: embed
the-embed-element.summary: The HTML <embed> element embeds external content at the specified point in the document. This content is provided by an external application or other source of interactive content such as a browser plug-in.
the-embed-element.title: <embed>: The Embed External Content element

the-fieldset-element.name: fieldset
the-fieldset-element.summary: The HTML <fieldset> element is used to group several controls as well as labels (<label>) within a web form.

chrome.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

chrome_android.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

opera.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

opera_android.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

webview_android.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

edge_blink.notes: Does not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

the-fieldset-element.title: <fieldset>: The Field Set element

the-figcaption-element.name: figcaption
the-figcaption-element.summary: The HTML <figcaption> or Figure Caption element represents a caption or legend describing the rest of the contents of its parent <figure> element.
the-figcaption-element.title: <figcaption>: The Figure Caption element

the-figure-element.name: figure
the-figure-element.summary: The HTML <figure> (Figure With Optional Caption) element represents self-contained content, potentially with an optional caption, which is specified using the (<figcaption>) element.
the-figure-element.title: <figure>: The Figure with Optional Caption element

the-footer-element.name: footer
the-footer-element.summary: The HTML <footer> element represents a footer for its nearest sectioning content or sectioning root element. A footer typically contains information about the author of the section, copyright data or links to related documents.
the-footer-element.title: <footer>

the-form-element.name: form
the-form-element.summary: The HTML <form> element represents a document section containing interactive controls for submitting information.
the-form-element.title: <form>

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h1
