the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h5
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The HTML <h1><h6> elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h6
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The HTML <h1><h6> elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-head-element.name: head
the-head-element.summary: The HTML <head> element contains machine-readable information (metadata) about the document, like its title, scripts, and style sheets.
the-head-element.title: <head>: The Document Metadata (Header) element

the-header-element.name: header
the-header-element.summary: The HTML <header> element represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also a logo, a search form, an author name, and other elements.
the-header-element.title: <header>

the-hgroup-element.name: hgroup
the-hgroup-element.summary: The HTML <hgroup> element represents a multi-level heading for a section of a document. It groups a set of <h1><h6> elements.
the-hgroup-element.title: <hgroup>

the-hr-element.name: hr
the-hr-element.summary: The HTML <hr> element represents a thematic break between paragraph-level elements: for example, a change of scene in a story, or a shift of topic within a section.
the-hr-element.title: <hr>: The Thematic Break (Horizontal Rule) element

the-html-element.name: html
the-html-element.summary: The HTML <html> element represents the root (top-level element) of an HTML document, so it is also referred to as the root element. All other elements must be descendants of this element.
the-html-element.title: <html>: The HTML Document / Root element

the-i-element.name: i
the-i-element.summary: The HTML Idiomatic Text element (<i>) represents a range of text that is set off from the normal text for some reason, such as idiomatic text, technical terms, taxonomical designations, among others.
the-i-element.title: <i>: The Idiomatic Text element

the-iframe-element.name: iframe
the-iframe-element.summary: The HTML Inline Frame element (<iframe>) represents a nested browsing context, embedding another HTML page into the current one.

firefox.notes: The resize CSS property doesn't have any effect on this element due to bug 680823.

firefox_android.notes: The resize CSS property doesn't have any effect on this element due to bug 680823.

safari.notes: Safari has a bug that prevents iframes from loading if the iframe element was hidden when added to the page. iframeElement.src = iframeElement.src should cause it to load the iframe.

safari_ios.notes: Safari has a bug that prevents iframes from loading if the iframe element was hidden when added to the page. iframeElement.src = iframeElement.src should cause it to load the iframe.

the-iframe-element.title: <iframe>: The Inline Frame element

lazy-loading-attributes.name: loading
lazy-loading-attributes.summary: Lazy loading is a strategy to identify resources as non-blocking (non-critical) and load these only when needed. It's a way to shorten the length of the critical rendering path, which translates into reduced page load times.

firefox_android.notes: See bug 1542784

caniuse.title: Lazy loading via attribute for images & iframes

lazy-loading-attributes.title: Lazy loading

the-img-element.name: img
the-img-element.summary: The HTML element embeds an image into the document.
the-img-element.title: : The Image Embed element

button-state-(type=button).name: input-button
button-state-(type=button).summary: <input> elements of type button are rendered as simple push buttons, which can be programmed to control custom functionality anywhere on a webpage as required when assigned an event handler function (typically for the click event).
button-state-(type=button).title: <input type="button">

checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).name: input-checkbox
checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).summary: <input> elements of type checkbox are rendered by default as boxes that are checked (ticked) when activated, like you might see in an official government paper form. The exact appearance depends upon the operating system configuration under which the browser is running. Generally this is a square but it may have rounded corners. A checkbox allows you to select single values for submission in a form (or not).
checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).title: <input type="checkbox">

color-state-(type=color).name: input-color
color-state-(type=color).summary: <input> elements of type color provide a user interface element that lets a user specify a color, either by using a visual color picker interface or by entering the color into a text field in #rrggbb hexadecimal format.

firefox.notes: Firefox doesn't yet support inputs of type color on Windows Touch.

color-state-(type=color).title: <input type="color">

date-state-(type=date).name: input-date
date-state-(type=date).summary: <input> elements of type="date" create input fields that let the user enter a date, either with a textbox that validates the input or a special date picker interface.

safari.notes: The input type is recognized, but there is no date-specific control. See bug 119175.

date-state-(type=date).title: <input type="date">

local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.name: input-datetime-local
local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.summary: <input> elements of type datetime-local create input controls that let the user easily enter both a date and a time, including the year, month, and day as well as the time in hours and minutes.

firefox.notes: See bug 888320 and TPE DOM/Date time input types.

safari.notes: The input type is recognized, but there is no date-specific control. See bug 200416.

local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.title: <input type="datetime-local">

email-state-(type=email).name: input-email
email-state-(type=email).summary: <input> elements of type email are used to let the user enter and edit an e-mail address, or, if the multiple attribute is specified, a list of e-mail addresses.

notes: Doesn't do validation, but instead offers a custom 'email' keyboard, which is designed to make entering email addresses easier.
The custom 'email' keyboard does not provide a comma key, so users cannot enter multiple email addresses.
Automatically applies a default style of opacity: 0.4 to disable textual <input> elements, including those of type 'email'. Other major browsers don't currently share this particular default style.

email-state-(type=email).title: <input type="email">

file-upload-state-(type=file).name: input-file
file-upload-state-(type=file).summary: <input> elements with type="file" let the user choose one or more files from their device storage. Once chosen, the files can be uploaded to a server using form submission, or manipulated using JavaScript code and the File API.

firefox.notes: You can set as well as get the value of HTMLInputElement.files in all modern browsers; this was most recently added to Firefox, in version 57 (see bug 1384030).

file-upload-state-(type=file).title: <input type="file">

hidden-state-(type=hidden).name: input-hidden
hidden-state-(type=hidden).summary: <input> elements of type hidden let web developers include data that cannot be seen or modified by users when a form is submitted. For example, the ID of the content that is currently being ordered or edited, or a unique security token. Hidden inputs are completely invisible in the rendered page, and there is no way to make it visible in the page's content.
hidden-state-(type=hidden).title: <input type="hidden">

image-button-state-(type=image).name: input-image
image-button-state-(type=image).summary: <input> elements of type image are used to create graphical submit buttons, i.e. submit buttons that take the form of an image rather than text.
image-button-state-(type=image).title: <input type="image">

the-input-element.name: input
the-input-element.summary: The HTML <input> element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent.
the-input-element.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

the-input-element.name: input
the-input-element.summary: The HTML <input> element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent.
the-input-element.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

month-state-(type=month).name: input-month
month-state-(type=month).summary: <input> elements of type month create input fields that let the user enter a month and year allowing a month and year to be easily entered. The value is a string whose value is in the format "YYYY-MM", where YYYY is the four-digit year and MM is the month number.

firefox.notes: See bug 888320.

safari.notes: The input type is recognized, but there is no month-specific control. See bug 200416.

month-state-(type=month).title: <input type="month">

number-state-(type=number).name: input-number
number-state-(type=number).summary: <input> elements of type number are used to let the user enter a number. They include built-in validation to reject non-numerical entries.
number-state-(type=number).title: <input type="number">

password-state-(type=password).name: input-password
password-state-(type=password).summary: <input> elements of type password provide a way for the user to securely enter a password.
password-state-(type=password).title: <input type="password">

radio-button-state-(type=radio).name: input-radio
radio-button-state-(type=radio).summary: <input> elements of type radio are generally used in radio groupscollections of radio buttons describing a set of related options.
radio-button-state-(type=radio).title: <input type="radio">

range-state-(type=range).name: input-range
range-state-(type=range).summary: <input> elements of type range let the user specify a numeric value which must be no less than a given value, and no more than another given value. The precise value, however, is not considered important. This is typically represented using a slider or dial control rather than a text entry box like the number input type.

webview_android.notes: Pre-Chromium Android WebView recognizes the range type, but doesn't implement a range-specific control.

range-state-(type=range).title: <input type="range">

reset-button-state-(type=reset).name: input-reset
reset-button-state-(type=reset).summary: <input> elements of type reset are rendered as buttons, with a default click event handler that resets all of the inputs in the form to their initial values.

firefox.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a <button> across page loads. Use the autocomplete attribute to control this feature.

firefox_android.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a <button> across page loads. Use the autocomplete attribute to control this feature.

reset-button-state-(type=reset).title: <input type="reset">

text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.name: input-search
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.summary: <input> elements of type search are text fields designed for the user to enter search queries into. These are functionally identical to text inputs, but may be styled differently by the user agent.
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.title: <input type="search">

text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.name: input-text
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.summary: <input> elements of type text create basic single-line text fields.
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.title: <input type="text">

submit-button-state-(type=submit).name: input-submit
submit-button-state-(type=submit).summary: <input> elements of type submit are rendered as buttons. When the click event occurs (typically because the user clicked the button), the user agent attempts to submit the form to the server.

firefox.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a

firefox_android.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a

submit-button-state-(type=submit).title: <input type="submit">

telephone-state-(type=tel).name: input-tel
telephone-state-(type=tel).summary: <input> elements of type tel are used to let the user enter and edit a telephone number. Unlike <input type="email"> and <input type="url"> , the input value is not automatically validated to a particular format before the form can be submitted, because formats for telephone numbers vary so much around the world.

chrome.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

safari.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

edge_blink.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

telephone-state-(type=tel).title: <input type="tel">

time-state-(type=time).name: input-time
time-state-(type=time).summary: <input> elements of type time create input fields designed to let the user easily enter a time (hours and minutes, and optionally seconds).
time-state-(type=time).title: <input type="time">

url-state-(type=url).name: input-url
url-state-(type=url).summary: <input> elements of type url are used to let the user enter and edit a URL.
url-state-(type=url).title: <input type="url">

week-state-(type=week).name: input-week
week-state-(type=week).summary: <input> elements of type week create input fields allowing easy entry of a year plus the ISO 8601 week number during that year (i.e., week 1 to 52 or 53).

firefox.notes: See bug 888320.

week-state-(type=week).title: <input type="week">

the-ins-element.name: ins
the-ins-element.summary: The HTML <ins> element represents a range of text that has been added to a document.
the-ins-element.title: <ins>

the-kbd-element.name: kbd
the-kbd-element.summary: The HTML Keyboard Input element (<kbd>) represents a span of inline text denoting textual user input from a keyboard, voice input, or any other text entry device.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, creating a <kbd> element incorrectly resulted in an HTMLSpanElement object, instead of the expected HTMLElement.

the-kbd-element.title: <kbd>: The Keyboard Input element

the-label-element.name: label
the-label-element.summary: The HTML <label> element represents a caption for an item in a user interface.
the-label-element.title: <label>

the-legend-element.name: legend
the-legend-element.summary: The HTML <legend> element represents a caption for the content of its parent <fieldset>.
the-legend-element.title: <legend>

the-li-element.name: li
the-li-element.summary: The HTML <li> element is used to represent an item in a list.
the-li-element.title: <li>

rel-alternate.name: alternate_stylesheet
rel-alternate.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
rel-alternate.title: Alternative style sheets

the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.name: alternate_stylesheet
the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.title: Alternative style sheets

attr-style-title.name: alternate_stylesheet
attr-style-title.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
attr-style-title.title: Alternative style sheets

attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.name: alternate_stylesheet
attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.title: Alternative style sheets

link-type-dns-prefetch.name: dns-prefetch
link-type-dns-prefetch.summary: The dns-prefetch keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need resources from the target resource's origin, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively performing DNS resolution for that origin.
link-type-dns-prefetch.title: Link types: dns-prefetch

link-type-modulepreload.name: modulepreload
link-type-modulepreload.summary: The modulepreload keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element provides a declarative way to preemptively fetch a module script and its dependencies, and store them in the document's module map for later evaluation.
link-type-modulepreload.title: Link types: modulepreload

link-type-preconnect.name: preconnect
link-type-preconnect.summary: The preconnect keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need resources from the target resource's origin, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively  initiating a connection to that origin.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 41, it doesn't obey the crossorigin attribute.

firefox_android.notes: Before Firefox 41, it doesn't obey the crossorigin attribute.

link-type-preconnect.title: Link types: preconnect

link-type-prefetch.name: prefetch
link-type-prefetch.summary: The prefetch keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need the target resource for future navigations, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively fetching and caching the resource.
link-type-prefetch.title: Link types: prefetch

link-type-preload.name: preload
link-type-preload.summary: The preload keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element indicates the user is highly likely to require the target resource for the current navigation, and therefore the browser must preemptively fetch and cache the resource.

firefox.notes: Disabled due to various web compatibility issues (e.g. bug 1405761).

firefox_android.notes: Disabled due to various web compatibility issues (e.g. bug 1405761).

link-type-preload.title: Link types: preload

link-type-prerender.name: prerender
link-type-prerender.summary: The prerender keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user might need the target resource for the next navigation, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively fetching and processing the resource  for example, by fetching its subresources or performing some rendering in the background offscreen.
link-type-prerender.title: Link types: prerender

the-link-element.name: link
the-link-element.summary: The HTML External Resource Link element (<link>) specifies relationships between the current document and an external resource. This element is most commonly used to link to stylesheets, but is also used to establish site icons (both "favicon" style icons and icons for the home screen and apps on mobile devices) among other things.
the-link-element.title: <link>: The External Resource Link element

the-main-element.name: main
the-main-element.summary: The HTML <main> element represents the dominant content of the <body> of a document. The main content area consists of content that is directly related to or expands upon the central topic of a document, or the central functionality of an application.
the-main-element.title: <main>

the-map-element.name: map
the-map-element.summary: The HTML <map> element is used with <area> elements to define an image map (a clickable link area).

notes: Before Firefox 5, in Quirks Mode, empty maps were no longer skipped over in favor of non-empty ones when matching.

Before Firefox 17, the default styling of the <map> HTML element was display: block;. This is now display: inline; and matches the behavior of the other browsers. It was already the case in Quirks Mode.

the-map-element.title: <map>

the-mark-element.name: mark
the-mark-element.summary: The HTML Mark Text element (<mark>) represents text which is marked or highlighted for reference or notation purposes, due to the marked passage's relevance or importance in the enclosing context.
the-mark-element.title: <mark>: The Mark Text element

the-menu-element.name: menu
the-menu-element.summary: The HTML <menu> element represents a group of commands that a user can perform or activate. This includes both list menus, which might appear across the top of a screen, as well as context menus, such as those that might appear underneath a button after it has been clicked.

firefox_android.notes: Nested menus are not supported.

the-menu-element.title: <menu>

meta-theme-color.name: theme-color
meta-theme-color.summary: The theme-color value for the name attribute of the <meta> element indicates a suggested color that user agents should use to customize the display of the page or of the surrounding user interface. If specified, the content attribute must contain a valid CSS <color>.

chrome.notes: Desktop Chrome only uses the color on installed progressive web apps. (Per caniuse.com.)
Desktop Chrome 39-72 claimed to have support, but did not actually use the color anywhere. Chrome for Android did use the color in the toolbar. (Per caniuse.com.)

chrome_android.notes: Chrome for Android does not use the color on devices with native dark-mode enabled. (Per caniuse.com.)

edge_blink.notes: Desktop Chrome only uses the color on installed progressive web apps. (Per caniuse.com.)
Desktop Chrome 39-72 claimed to have support, but did not actually use the color anywhere. Chrome for Android did use the color in the toolbar. (Per caniuse.com.)

meta-theme-color.title: theme-color

standard-metadata-names.name: name
standard-metadata-names.summary: The <meta> element can be used to provide document metadata in terms of name-value pairs, with the name attribute giving the metadata name, and the content attribute giving the value.
standard-metadata-names.title: Standard metadata names

the-meta-element.name: meta
the-meta-element.summary: The HTML <meta> element represents metadata that cannot be represented by other HTML meta-related elements, like <base>, <link>, <script>, <style> or <title>.
the-meta-element.title: <meta>: The Document-level Metadata element

the-meter-element.name: meter
the-meter-element.summary: The HTML <meter> element represents either a scalar value within a known range or a fractional value.
the-meter-element.title: <meter>: The HTML Meter element

the-nav-element.name: nav
the-nav-element.summary: The HTML <nav> element represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents. Common examples of navigation sections are menus, tables of contents, and indexes.
the-nav-element.title: <nav>: The Navigation Section element

the-noscript-element.name: noscript
the-noscript-element.summary: The HTML <noscript> element defines a section of HTML to be inserted if a script type on the page is unsupported or if scripting is currently turned off in the browser.
the-noscript-element.title: <noscript>

the-object-element.name: object
the-object-element.summary: The HTML <object> element represents an external resource, which can be treated as an image, a nested browsing context, or a resource to be handled by a plugin.
the-object-element.title: <object>

the-ol-element.name: ol
the-ol-element.summary: The HTML <ol> element represents an ordered list of items  typically rendered as a numbered list.
the-ol-element.title: <ol>: The Ordered List element

the-optgroup-element.name: optgroup
the-optgroup-element.summary: The HTML <optgroup> element creates a grouping of options within a <select> element.
the-optgroup-element.title: <optgroup>

the-option-element.name: option
the-option-element.summary: The HTML <option> element is used to define an item contained in a <select>, an <optgroup>, or a <datalist> element. As such, <option> can represent menu items in popups and other lists of items in an HTML document.
the-option-element.title: <option>: The HTML Option element

the-output-element.name: output
the-output-element.summary: The HTML Output element (<output>) is a container element into which a site or app can inject the results of a calculation or the outcome of a user action.
the-output-element.title: <output>: The Output element

the-p-element.name: p
the-p-element.summary:
The HTML

element represents a paragraph.
the-p-element.title: : The Paragraph element

the-param-element.name: param
the-param-element.summary: The HTML <param> element defines parameters for an <object> element.
the-param-element.title: <param>: The Object Parameter element

the-picture-element.name: picture
the-picture-element.summary: The HTML element contains zero or more elements and one element to offer alternative versions of an image for different display/device scenarios.
the-picture-element.title: <picture>: The Picture element

the-pre-element.name: pre
the-pre-element.summary: The HTML <pre> element represents preformatted text which is to be presented exactly as written in the HTML file.
the-pre-element.title: <pre>: The Preformatted Text element

the-progress-element.name: progress
the-progress-element.summary: The HTML <progress> element displays an indicator showing the completion progress of a task, typically displayed as a progress bar.

notes: Prior to Firefox 14, the <progress> element was incorrectly classified as a form element, and therefore had a form attribute. This has been fixed.
Firefox provides the ::-moz-progress-bar pseudo-element, which lets you style the part of the interior of the progress bar representing the amount of work completed so far.
Prior to Firefox 14, the <progress> element was incorrectly classified as a form element, and therefore had a form attribute. This has been fixed.
Firefox provides the ::-moz-progress-bar pseudo-element, which lets you style the part of the interior of the progress bar representing the amount of work completed so far.

safari_ios.notes: Safari on iOS does not support indeterminate progress bars (they are rendered like 0%-completed progress bars).

the-progress-element.title: <progress>: The Progress Indicator element

the-q-element.name: q
the-q-element.summary: The HTML <q> element  indicates that the enclosed text is a short inline quotation. Most modern browsers implement this by surrounding the text in quotation marks.
the-q-element.title: <q>: The Inline Quotation element

the-rp-element.name: rp
the-rp-element.summary: The HTML Ruby Fallback Parenthesis (<rp>) element is used to provide fall-back parentheses for browsers that do not support display of ruby annotations using the <ruby> element.
the-rp-element.title: <rp>: The Ruby Fallback Parenthesis element

the-rt-element.name: rt
the-rt-element.summary: The HTML Ruby Text (<rt>) element specifies the ruby text component of a ruby annotation, which is used to provide pronunciation, translation, or transliteration information for East Asian typography. The <rt> element must always be contained within a <ruby> element.
the-rt-element.title: <rt>: The Ruby Text element

the-ruby-element.name: ruby
the-ruby-element.summary: The HTML <ruby> element represents small annotations that are rendered above, below, or next to base text, usually used for showing the pronunciation of East Asian characters. It can also be used for annotating other kinds of text, but this usage is less common.
the-ruby-element.title: <ruby>

the-s-element.name: s
the-s-element.summary: The HTML <s> element renders text with a strikethrough, or a line through it. Use the <s> element to represent things that are no longer relevant or no longer accurate. However, <s> is not appropriate when indicating document edits; for that, use the <del> and <ins> elements, as appropriate.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-s-element.title: <s>

the-samp-element.name: samp
the-samp-element.summary: The HTML Sample Element (<samp>) is used to enclose inline text which represents sample (or quoted) output from a computer program.
the-samp-element.title: <samp>: The Sample Output element

the-script-element.name: script
the-script-element.summary: The HTML <script> element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 4, inserting <script> elements that have been created by calling document.createElement("script") no longer enforces execution in insertion order. This change lets Firefox properly abide by the specification. To make script-inserted external scripts execute in their insertion order, set .async=false on them.

the-script-element.title: <script>: The Script element

the-section-element.name: section
the-section-element.summary: The HTML <section> element represents a standalone section  which doesn't have a more specific semantic element to represent it  contained within an HTML document.
the-section-element.title: <section>: The Generic Section element

the-select-element.name: select
the-select-element.summary: The HTML <select> element represents a control that provides a menu of options

chrome.notes: border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

chrome_android.notes: border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

firefox.notes: Historically, Firefox has allowed keyboard and mouse events to bubble up from the <option> element to the parent <select> element, although this behavior is inconsistent across many browsers. For better Web compatibility (and for technical reasons), when Firefox is in multi-process mode the <select> element is displayed as a drop-down list. The behavior is unchanged if the <select> is presented inline and it has either the multiple attribute defined or a size attribute set to more than 1. Rather than watching <option> elements for events, you should watch for change events on <select>. See bug 1090602 for details.

firefox_android.notes: Firefox for Android, by default, sets a background-image gradient on all <select multiple> elements. This can be disabled using background-image: none.

workers.name: Using_web_workers
workers.summary: Web Workers are a simple means for web content to run scripts in background threads. The worker thread can perform tasks without interfering with the user interface. In addition, they can perform I/O using XMLHttpRequest (although the responseXML and channel attributes are always null). Once created, a worker can send messages to the JavaScript code that created it by posting messages to an event handler specified by that code (and vice versa).
